[start section id="20112"]

#1 Moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of low rectum status-post radiation and concurrent chemotherapy with evidence of dys-response, but subsequent progression in the absence of any resection
#2 Mild hypercalcemia and thrombocytopenia
#3 Anorectal pain with no clinical evidence of abscess likely related to tumor
#4 Nicotine addiction
#5 History of alcohol use with fatty liver disease.
PLAN
At this time based on his disease extent, we would recommend evaluation by an anorectal surgeon.  I do note that he is going to see Dr. Martinez later today.  We would get a preoperative EKG.  In addition, would get PT, PTT.  If he is deemed a candidate for surgery after TME, we would recommend adjuvant FOLFOX6 therapy (a total of eight cycles).  In addition, I would check a K-ras mutation status on this tumor.  I have advised him against smoking and drinking and have offered help.  He would like to think about this.  He has not made-up his mind about receiving post-op chemotherapy closer to home or here.
Addendum: His EKG and CXR are unremarkable I do not see any barriers for surgery.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

