[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Miller Lee Locke is a very pleasant 57-year-old gentleman from Texas 07856, who has the following oncologic history:
1.  February 2009 he started to experience "abdominal pain and bloating with altered bowel movements."  He states that he had a feeling of incomplete evacuation, constipation with occasional diarrhea.  He denied any hematochezia at that time but did experience severe fatigue over the course of two-months.  He did note that his stool color was "tan" mixed with mucus.  He was given some medications for the pain which did not resolve, and eventually by June of 2009 he required enemas.  In addition, per records he had a perineal abscess drained in the spring of 2009.  In July 2009 he underwent a colonoscopy.
The colonoscopy revealed a low rectal mass that was noncircumferential.  It was fungating, infiltrative, ulcerated, and about 4-cm in diameter.  It involved one-third circumference in the posterior wall.  In addition, a 4-mm polyp in the rectosigmoid colon was noted at 20 cm proximal to the anus.  This mass was invasive, moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.  He denies any history of rectal prolapse but states that he had recurrent abscesses in the perineal region which were drained.  He denies any history of inflammatory bowel disease.
2. August through end of September 2009 he underwent radiation therapy with concurrent Xeloda.  He states that this was given over a period of six-weeks, and towards the end of radiation he started to have hematuria, was found to have urinary tract infection and was treated with antibiotics.  This therapy was given with the idea of neoadjuvant approach.  Subsequently, he had an MRI of the pelvis on November 17, 2009.  This demonstrated a significant reduction in the anorectal wall thickening that was measuring 0.9-cm in thickness from a previous 1.7-cm on July 2009 CT-scan.  There was no tumor extension evident on this MRI apparently.  The residual enhancement in this area was suggestive of inflammation versus persistent viable tumor.  After discussion with his surgeon, he elected to wait since he had had a good response.  He underwent a CT-scan of the chest, abdomen, pelvis with contrast on January 26, 2010.  This again demonstrated continued but improved rectosigmoid junction wall thickening measuring 1.3-cm.  This was compared with the CT-scan of July which showed 1.8-cm thick mass in the same region.  There were no enlarged lymph nodes identified within the abdomen or pelvis.  There was a suggestion of fatty infiltration of liver.  No lesions were noted on the CT-scan of the chest.
3. January 26, 2010, he underwent another pelvic MRI which showed stability of this mass which measured 10-mm.
4. March 8, 2010, he underwent another follow-up MRI which showed that the rectal mass located at 2.5-cm from the anal verge measuring 3-cm in length.  The mass appeared annular.  The mass involved approximately half of the circumference of the rectum.  There was local invasion of the mass through the muscularis approximately 3 to 4-mm.  Due to location of the mass there was extension to the mesorectal fascia with the mass also contacting the levator ani.  There were no suspicious adjacent lymph nodes noted.  He was again advised surgery, but opted against it.
Currently, he states that he does have occasional anal pain and has noticed mucus in his stools.  He denies any fever, chills, weight-loss, loss of appetite, headaches, shortness-of-breath, cough, or chest pain.  He denies any gastroesophageal reflux symptoms.

